211
00:21:45 --> 00:22:02
proclaim, democracy is not just formal elections.
(Applause.) When journalists are put behind

212
00:22:02 --> 00:22:08
bars for doing their jobs, or activists are
threatened as governments crack down on civil

213
00:22:08 --> 00:22:17
society -- (applause) -- then you may have
democracy in name, but not in substance. (Applause.)

214
00:22:17 --> 00:22:23
And I&#39;m convinced that nations cannot realize
the full promise of independence until they

215
00:22:23 --> 00:22:27
fully protect the rights of their people.

216
00:22:27 --> 00:22:34
And this is true even for countries that have
made important democratic progress. As I indicated

217
00:22:34 --> 00:22:42
during my visit to Kenya, the remarkable gains
that country has made with a new constitution,

218
00:22:42 --> 00:22:50
with its election, cannot be jeopardized by
restrictions on civil society. Likewise, our

219
00:22:50 --> 00:22:56
host, Ethiopians have much to be proud of
-- I&#39;ve been amazed at all the wonderful work

220
00:22:56 --> 00:23:00
that&#39;s being done here -- and it&#39;s true that
the elections that took place here occurred

221
00:23:00 --> 00:23:04
without violence. But as I discussed with
Prime Minister Hailemariam, that’s just

222
00:23:04 --> 00:23:09
the start of democracy. I believe Ethiopia
will not fully unleash the potential of its

223
00:23:09 --> 00:23:16
people if journalists are restricted or legitimate
opposition groups can&#39;t participate in the

224
00:23:16 --> 00:23:20
campaign process. And, to his credit, the
Prime Minister acknowledged that more work

225
00:23:20 --> 00:23:29
will need to be done for Ethiopia to be a
full-fledged, sustainable democracy. (Applause.)

226
00:23:29 --> 00:23:35
So these are conversations we have to have
as friends. Our American democracy is not

227
00:23:35 --> 00:23:46
perfect. We&#39;ve worked for many years -- (applause)
-- but one thing we do is we continually reexamine

228
00:23:46 --> 00:23:50
to figure out how can we make our democracy
better. And that&#39;s a force of strength for

229
00:23:50 --> 00:23:58
us, being willing to look and see honestly
what we need to be doing to fulfill the promise

230
00:23:58 --> 00:24:00
of our founding documents.

231
00:24:00 --> 00:24:08
And every country has to go through that process.
No country is perfect, but we have to be honest,

232
00:24:08 --> 00:24:17
and strive to expand freedoms, to broaden
democracy. The bottom line is that when citizens

233
00:24:17 --> 00:24:22
cannot exercise their rights, the world has
a responsibility to speak out. And America

234
00:24:22 --> 00:24:27
will, even if it’s sometimes uncomfortable
-- (applause) -- even when it’s sometimes

235
00:24:27 --> 00:24:28
directed toward our friends.

236
00:24:28 --> 00:24:33
And I know that there’s some countries that
don&#39;t say anything -- (laughter) -- and maybe

237
00:24:33 --> 00:24:40
that&#39;s easier for leaders to deal with. (Laughter.)
But you&#39;re kind of stuck with us -- this is

238
00:24:40 --> 00:24:44
how we are. (Applause.) We believe in these
things and we&#39;re going to keep on talking

239
00:24:44 --> 00:24:44
about them.

240
00:24:44 --> 00:24:49
And I want to repeat, we do this not because
we think our democracy is perfect, or we think

241
00:24:49 --> 00:24:53
that every country has to follow precisely
our path. For more than two centuries since

242
00:24:53 --> 00:24:57
our independence, we’re still working on
perfecting our union. We&#39;re not immune from

243
00:24:57 --> 00:25:04
criticism. When we fall short of our ideals,
we strive to do better. (Applause.) But when

244
00:25:04 --> 00:25:10
we speak out for our principles, at home and
abroad, we stay true to our values and we

245
00:25:10 --> 00:25:17
help lift up the lives of people beyond our
borders. And we think that&#39;s important. And

246
00:25:17 --> 00:25:22
it&#39;s especially important, I believe, for
those of us of African descent, because we&#39;ve

247
00:25:22 --> 00:25:28
known what it feels like to be on the receiving
end of injustice. We know what it means to

248
00:25:28 --> 00:25:35
be discriminated against. (Applause.) We know
what it means to be jailed. So how can we

249
00:25:35 --> 00:25:39
stand by when it&#39;s happening to somebody else?

250
00:25:39 --> 00:25:43
I&#39;ll be frank with you, it can&#39;t just be America
that&#39;s talking about these things. Fellow

251
00:25:43 --> 00:25:50
African countries have to talk about these
things. (Applause.) Just as other countries

252
00:25:50 --> 00:25:57
championed your break from colonialism, our
nations must all raise our voices when universal

253
00:25:57 --> 00:26:04
rights are being denied. For if we truly believe
that Africans are equal in dignity, then Africans

254
00:26:04 --> 00:26:09
have an equal right to freedoms that are universal
-- that’s a principle we all have to defend.

255
00:26:09 --> 00:26:17
(Applause.) And it&#39;s not just a Western idea;
it&#39;s a human idea.

256
00:26:17 --> 00:26:24
I have to also say that Africa’s democratic
progress is also at risk when leaders refuse

257
00:26:24 --> 00:26:39
to step aside when their terms end. (Applause.)
Now, let me be honest with you -- I do not

258
00:26:39 --> 00:26:51
understand this. (Laughter.) I am in my second
term. It has been an extraordinary privilege

259
00:26:51 --> 00:26:55
for me to serve as President of the United
States. I cannot imagine a greater honor or

260
00:26:55 --> 00:27:05
a more interesting job. I love my work. But
under our Constitution, I cannot run again.

261
00:27:05 --> 00:27:13
(Laughter and applause.) I can&#39;t run again.
I actually think I&#39;m a pretty good President

262
00:27:13 --> 00:27:15
-- I think if I ran I could win. (Laughter
and applause.) But I can&#39;t.

263
00:27:15 --> 00:27:34
So there’s a lot that I&#39;d like to do to
keep America moving, but the law is the law.

264
00:27:34 --> 00:27:43
(Applause.) And no one person is above the
law. Not even the President. (Applause.) And

265
00:27:43 --> 00:27:50
I&#39;ll be honest with you -- I’m looking forward
to life after being President. (Laughter.)

266
00:27:50 --> 00:27:54
I won&#39;t have such a big security detail all
the time. (Laughter.) It means I can go take

267
00:27:54 --> 00:28:00
a walk. I can spend time with my family. I
can find other ways to serve. I can visit

268
00:28:00 --> 00:28:13
Africa more often. (Applause.) The point is,
I don&#39;t understand why people want to stay

269
00:28:13 --> 00:28:26
so long. (Laughter.) Especially when they’ve
got a lot of money. (Laughter and applause.)

270
00:28:26 --> 00:28:38
When a leader tries to change the rules in
the middle of the game just to stay in office,

271
00:28:38 --> 00:28:49
it risks instability and strife -- as we’ve
seen in Burundi. (Applause.) And this is often

272
00:28:49 --> 00:28:54
just a first step down a perilous path. And
sometimes you’ll hear leaders say, well,

273
00:28:54 --> 00:28:59
I&#39;m the only person who can hold this nation
together. (Laughter.) If that&#39;s true, then

274
00:28:59 --> 00:29:03
that leader has failed to truly build their
nation. (Applause.)

275
00:29:03 --> 00:29:11
You look at Nelson Mandela -- Madiba, like
George Washington, forged a lasting legacy

276
00:29:11 --> 00:29:14
not only because of what they did in office,
but because they were willing to leave office

277
00:29:14 --> 00:29:25
and transfer power peacefully. (Applause.)
And just as the African Union has condemned

278
00:29:25 --> 00:29:31
coups and illegitimate transfers of power,
the AU’s authority and strong voice can

279
00:29:31 --> 00:29:35
also help the people of Africa ensure that
their leaders abide by term limits and their

280
00:29:35 --> 00:29:39
constitutions. (Applause.) Nobody should be
president for life.

281
00:29:39 --> 00:29:50
And your country is better off if you have
new blood and new ideas. (Applause.) I&#39;m still

282
00:29:50 --> 00:29:58
a pretty young man, but I know that somebody
with new energy and new insights will be good

283
00:29:58 --> 00:30:06
for my country. (Applause.) It will be good
for yours, too, in some cases.

284
00:30:06 --> 00:30:11
Africa’s progress will also depend on security
and peace -- because an essential part of

285
00:30:11 --> 00:30:19
human dignity is being safe and free from
fear. In Angola, Mozambique, Liberia, Sierra

286
00:30:19 --> 00:30:27
Leone, we’ve seen conflicts end and countries
work to rebuild. But from Somalia and Nigeria

287
00:30:27 --> 00:30:33
to Mali and Tunisia, terrorists continue to
target innocent civilians. Many of these groups

288
00:30:33 --> 00:30:38
claim the banner of religion, but hundreds
of millions of African Muslims know that Islam

289
00:30:38 --> 00:30:50
means peace. (Applause.) And we must call
groups
like al Qaeda, ISIL, al-Shabaab, Boko Haram

290
00:30:50 --> 00:30:58
-- we must call them what they are -- murderers.
(Applause.)

291
00:30:58 --> 00:31:03
In the face of threats, Africa -- and the
African Union --has shown leadership. Because

292
00:31:03 --> 00:31:07
of the AU force in Somalia,
al-Shabaab controls less territory and the

293
00:31:07 --> 00:31:13
Somali government is growing stronger. In
central Africa, the AU-led mission continues

294
00:31:13 --> 00:31:19
to degrade the Lord’s Resistance Army. In
the Lake Chad Basin, forces from several nations

295
00:31:19 --> 00:31:24
-- with the backing of the AU -- are fighting
to end Boko Haram’s senseless brutality.

296
00:31:24 --> 00:31:28
And today, we salute all those who serve to
protect the innocent, including so many brave

297
00:31:28 --> 00:31:30
African peacekeepers.

298
00:31:30 --> 00:31:35
Now, as Africa stands against terror and conflict,
I want you to know that the United States

299
00:31:35 --> 00:31:41
stands with you. With training and support,
we’re helping African forces grow stronger.

300
00:31:41 --> 00:31:45
The United States is supporting the AU’s
efforts to strengthen peacekeeping, and we’re

301
00:31:45 --> 00:31:49
working with countries in the region to deal
with emerging crises with the African Peacekeeping

302
00:31:49 --> 00:31:52
Rapid Response Partnership.

303
00:31:52 --> 00:31:56
The world must do more to help as well. This
fall at the United Nations, I will host a

304
00:31:56 --> 00:32:01
summit to secure new commitments to strengthen
international support for peacekeeping, including

305
00:32:01 --> 00:32:07
here in Africa. And building on commitments
that originated here in the AU, we’ll work

306
00:32:07 --> 00:32:11
to develop a new partnership between the U.N.
and the AU that can provide reliable support

307
00:32:11 --> 00:32:17
for AU peace operations. If African governments
and international partners step up with strong

308
00:32:17 --> 00:32:24
support, we can transform how we work together
to promote security and peace in Africa.

309
00:32:24 --> 00:32:27
Our efforts to ensure our shared security
must be matched by a commitment to improve

310
00:32:27 --> 00:32:33
governance. Those things are connected. Good
governance is one of the best weapons against

311
00:32:33 --> 00:32:38
terrorism and instability. Our fight against
terrorist groups, for example, will never

312
00:32:38 --> 00:32:45
be won if we fail to address legitimate grievances
that terrorists may try to exploit, if we

313
00:32:45 --> 00:32:50
don’t build trust with all communities,
if we don’t uphold the rule of law. There’s

314
00:32:50 --> 00:32:54
a saying, and I believe it is true -- if we
sacrifice liberty in the name of security,

315
00:32:54 --> 00:32:59
we risk losing both. (Applause.)

316
00:32:59 --> 00:33:06
This same seriousness of purpose is needed
to end conflicts. In the Central African Republic,

317
00:33:06 --> 00:33:11
the spirit of dialogue recently shown by ordinary
citizens must be matched by leaders committed

318
00:33:11 --> 00:33:17
to inclusive elections and a peaceful transition.
In Mali, the comprehensive peace agreement

319
00:33:17 --> 00:33:22
must be fulfilled. And leaders in Sudan must
know their nation will never truly thrive

320
00:33:22 --> 00:33:26
so long as they wage war against their own
people -- the world will not forget about

321
00:33:26 --> 00:33:26
Darfur.

322
00:33:26 --> 00:33:32
In South Sudan, the joy of independence has
descended into the despair of violence. I

323
00:33:32 --> 00:33:44
was there at the United Nations when we held
up South Sudan as the promise of a new beginning.

324
00:33:44 --> 00:33:48
And neither Mr. Kiir, nor Mr. Machar have
shown, so far, any interest in sparing their

325
00:33:48 --> 00:33:51
people from this suffering, or reaching a
political solution.

326
00:33:51 --> 00:33:57
Yesterday, I met with leaders from this region.
We agree that, given the current situation,

327
00:33:57 --> 00:34:03
Mr. Kiir and Mr. Machar must reach an agreement
by August 17th -- because if they do not,

328
00:34:03 --> 00:34:08
I believe the international community must
raise the costs of intransigence. And the

329
00:34:08 --> 00:34:12
world awaits the report of the AU Commission
of Inquiry, because accountability for atrocities

330
00:34:12 --> 00:34:21
must be part of any lasting peace in Africa’s
youngest nation. (Applause.)

331
00:34:21 --> 00:34:24
And finally, Africa’s progress will depend
on upholding the human rights of all people

332
00:34:24 --> 00:34:33
-- for if each of us is to be treated with
dignity, each of us must be sure to also extend

333
00:34:33 --> 00:34:39
that same dignity to others. As President,
I make it a point to meet with many of our

334
00:34:39 --> 00:34:43
Young African Leaders. And one was a young
man from Senegal. He said something wonderful

335
00:34:43 --> 00:34:49
about being together with so many of his African
brothers and sisters. He said, “Here, I

336
00:34:49 --> 00:34:56
have met Africa, the [Africa] I’ve always
believed in. She’s beautiful. She’s young.

337
00:34:56 --> 00:35:03
She’s full of talent and motivation and
ambition.” I agree.

338
00:35:03 --> 00:35:08
Africa is the beautiful, talented daughters
who are just as capable as Africa’s sons.

339
00:35:08 --> 00:35:14
(Applause.) And as a father, I believe that
my two daughters have to have the same chance

340
00:35:14 --> 00:35:20
to pursue their dreams as anybody’s son
-- and that same thing holds true for girls

341
00:35:20 --> 00:35:25
here in Africa. (Applause.) Our girls have
to be treated the same.

342
00:35:25 --> 00:35:31
We can’t let old traditions stand in the
way. The march of history shows that we have

343
00:35:31 --> 00:35:37
the capacity to broaden our moral imaginations.
We come to see that some traditions are good

344
00:35:37 --> 00:35:43
for us, they keep us grounded, but that, in
our modern world, other traditions set us

345
00:35:43 --> 00:35:52
back. When African girls are subjected to
the mutilation of their bodies, or forced

346
00:35:52 --> 00:35:59
into marriage at the ages of 9 or 10 or 11
-- that sets us back. That&#39;s not a good tradition.

347
00:35:59 --> 00:36:06
It needs to end. (Applause.)

348
00:36:06 --> 00:36:11
When more than 80 percent of new HIV cases
in the hardest-hit countries are teenage girls,

349
00:36:11 --> 00:36:17
that’s a tragedy; that sets us back. So
America is beginning a partnership with 10

350
00:36:17 --> 00:36:24
African countries -- Kenya, Lesotho, Malawi,
Mozambique, South Africa, Swaziland, Tanzania,

351
00:36:24 --> 00:36:29
Uganda, Zambia and Zimbabwe -- to keep teenage
girls safe and AIDS-free. (Applause.) And

352
00:36:29 --> 00:36:40
when girls cannot go to school and grow up
not knowing how to read or write -- that denies

353
00:36:40 --> 00:36:47
the world future women engineers, future women
doctors, future women business owners, future

354
00:36:47 --> 00:36:52
women presidents -- that sets us all back.
(Applause.) That&#39;s a bad tradition -- not

355
00:36:52 --> 00:36:57
providing our girls the same education as
our sons.

356
00:36:57 --> 00:37:01
I was saying in Kenya, nobody would put out
a football team and then just play half the

357
00:37:01 --> 00:37:12
team. You’d lose. (Applause.) the same is
true when it comes to getting everybody and

358
00:37:12 --> 00:37:20
education. You can&#39;t leave half the team off
-- our young women. So as part of America’s

359
00:37:20 --> 00:37:24
support for the education and the health of
our daughters, my wife, Michelle, is helping

360
00:37:24 --> 00:37:27
to lead a global campaign, including a new
effort in Tanzania and Malawi, with a simple

361
00:37:27 --> 00:37:33
message -- Let Girls Learn -- let girls learn
so they grow up healthy and they grow up strong.

362
00:37:33 --> 00:37:37
(Applause.) And that will be good for families.
And they will raise smart, healthy children,

363
00:37:37 --> 00:37:42
and that will be good for every one of your
nations.

364
00:37:42 --> 00:37:48
Africa is the beautiful, strong women that
these girls grow up to become. The single

365
00:37:48 --> 00:37:57
best indicator of whether a nation will succeed
is how it treats its women. (Applause.) When

366
00:37:57 --> 00:38:03
women have health care and women have education,
families are stronger, communities are more

367
00:38:03 --> 00:38:10
prosperous, children do better in school,
nations are more prosperous. Look at the amazing

368
00:38:10 --> 00:38:19
African women here in this hall. (Applause.)
If you want your country to grow and succeed,

369
00:38:19 --> 00:38:23
you have to empower your women. And if you
want to empower more women, America will be

370
00:38:23 --> 00:38:30
your partner. (Applause.)
Let’s work together to stop sexual assault

371
00:38:30 --> 00:38:35
and domestic violence. Let’s make clear
that we will not tolerate rape as a weapon

372
00:38:35 --> 00:38:41
of war -- it’s a crime. (Applause.) And
those who commit it must be punished. Let’s

373
00:38:41 --> 00:38:45
lift up the next generation of women leaders
who can help fight injustice and forge peace

374
00:38:45 --> 00:38:53
and start new businesses and create jobs -- and
some might hire some men, too. (Laughter.)

375
00:38:53 --> 00:39:02
We’ll all be better off when women have
equal futures.

376
00:39:02 --> 00:39:06
And Africa is the beautiful tapestry of your
cultures and ethnicities and races and religions.

377
00:39:06 --> 00:39:16
Last night, we saw this amazing dance troupe
made up of street children who had formed

378
00:39:16 --> 00:39:21
a dance troupe and they performed for the
Prime Minister and myself. And there were

379
00:39:21 --> 00:39:26
80 different languages and I don&#39;t know how
many ethnic groups. And there were like 30

380
00:39:26 --> 00:39:29
different dances that were being done. And
the Prime Minister was trying to keep up with

381
00:39:29 --> 00:39:40
-- okay, I think that one is -- (laughter)
-- and they were moving fast. And that diversity

382
00:39:40 --> 00:39:46
here in Ethiopia is representative of diversity
all throughout Africa. (Applause.) And that&#39;s

383
00:39:46 --> 00:39:46
a strength.

384
00:39:46 --> 00:39:52
Now, yesterday, I had the privilege to view
Lucy -- you may know Lucy -- she’s our ancestor,

385
00:39:52 --> 00:40:01
more than 3 million years old. (Applause.)
In this tree of humanity, with all of our

386
00:40:01 --> 00:40:09
branches and diversity, we all go back to
the same root. We’re all one family -- we&#39;re

387
00:40:09 --> 00:40:18
all one tribe. And yet so much of the suffering
in our world stems from our failure to remember

388
00:40:18 --> 00:40:24
that -- to not recognize ourselves in each
other. (Applause.)

389
00:40:24 --> 00:40:29
We think because somebody’s skin is slightly
different, or their hair is slightly different,

390
00:40:29 --> 00:40:37
or their religious faith is differently expressed,
or they speak a different language that it

391
00:40:37 --> 00:40:43
justifies somehow us treating them with less
dignity. And that becomes the source of so

392
00:40:43 --> 00:40:47
many of our problems. And we think somehow
that we make ourselves better by putting other

393
00:40:47 --> 00:40:53
people down. And that becomes the source of
so many of our problems. When we begin to

394
00:40:53 --> 00:41:00
see other as somehow less than ourselves -- when
we succumb to these artificial divisions of

395
00:41:00 --> 00:41:08
faith or sect or tribe or ethnicity -- then
even the most awful abuses are justified in

396
00:41:08 --> 00:41:14
the minds of those who are thinking in those
ways. And in the end, abusers lose their own

397
00:41:14 --> 00:41:21
humanity, as well. (Applause.)

398
00:41:21 --> 00:41:26
Nelson Mandela taught us, “to be free is
not merely to cast off one’s chains, but

399
00:41:26 --> 00:41:30
to live in a way that respects and enhances
the freedom of others.”

400
00:41:30 --> 00:41:34
Every one of us is equal. Every one of us
has worth. Every one of us matters. And when

401
00:41:34 --> 00:41:38
we respect the freedom of others -- no matter
the color of their skin, or how they pray

402
00:41:38 --> 00:41:49
or who they are or who they love -- we are
all more free. (Applause.) Your dignity depends

403
00:41:49 --> 00:41:55
on my dignity, and my dignity depends on yours.
Imagine if everyone had that spirit in their

404
00:41:55 --> 00:42:04
hearts. Imagine if governments operated that
way. (Applause.) Just imagine what the world

405
00:42:04 --> 00:42:08
could look like -- the future that we could
bequeath these young people.

406
00:42:08 --> 00:42:14
Yes, in our world, old thinking can be a stubborn
thing. That&#39;s one of the reasons why we need

407
00:42:14 --> 00:42:22
term limits -- old people think old ways.
And you can see my grey hair, I&#39;m getting

408
00:42:22 --> 00:42:28
old. (Laughter.) The old ways can be stubborn.
But I believe the human heart is stronger.

409
00:42:28 --> 00:42:33
I believe hearts can change. I believe minds
can open. That’s how change happens. That’s

410
00:42:33 --> 00:42:40
how societies move forward. It&#39;s not always
a straight line -- step by halting step -- sometimes

411
00:42:40 --> 00:42:45
you go forward, you move back a little bit.
But I believe we are marching, we are pointing

412
00:42:45 --> 00:42:48
towards ideals of justice and equality.

413
00:42:48 --> 00:42:54
That’s how your nations won independence
-- not just with rifles, but with principles

414
00:42:54 --> 00:42:58
and ideals. (Applause.) That&#39;s how African
Americans won our civil rights. That&#39;s how

415
00:42:58 --> 00:43:04
South Africans -- black and white -- tore
down apartheid. That&#39;s why I can stand before

416
00:43:04 --> 00:43:11
you today as the first African American President
of the United States. (Applause.)

417
00:43:11 --> 00:43:19
New thinking. Unleashing growth that creates
opportunity. Promoting development that lifts

418
00:43:19 --> 00:43:25
all people out of poverty. Supporting democracy
that gives citizens their say. Advancing the

419
00:43:25 --> 00:43:32
security and justice that delivers peace.
Respecting the human rights of all people.

420
00:43:32 --> 00:43:36
These are the keys to progress -- not just
in Africa, but around the world. And this

421
00:43:36 --> 00:43:37
is the work that we can do together.

422
00:43:37 --> 00:43:44
And I am hopeful. As I prepare to return home,
my thoughts are with that same young man from

423
00:43:44 --> 00:43:48
Senegal, who said: Here, I have met Africa,
the [Africa] I’ve always believed in. She’s

424
